  <discussion>Variation in the number of floral parts of Sedum leibergii (5–7-merous) is unique in North American sedums.  It has tiny rosettes of lax, long-spatulate basal leaves that mostly have shriveled by anthesis.  Sedum borschii, which is often confused with S. leibergii, has primary rosettes, prominent at anthesis, that have obovate or elliptic leaves.</discussion>
